Imagine a very long web page with many sections (for example, specifications on a single HTML page). If the user requests a specific section (for example, page.html#section7), what would happen if the web server streamed this section first, then the rest?
Stream order:
1. beginning of the HTML document until <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser would then ensure to insert sections 1 to 6 *above* section 7 on the web page.
Does that make sense to you? Could it be useful?
What I want to achieve is to render the linked section (#section7) as quickly as possible without having to reimplement anything with JavaScript. I just want a very long HTML document, but with the fastest possible rendering of the linked sections. This should work with plain HTML.
The content could be streamed in this way, then the browser would inject each <contents> into its <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would be streamed out of order, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it was streamed in order.
@user22 You can reorganize the documents like this even without JS. You cannot use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters to tell the server which section you want to see first. To reorder the parts, you have the choice between:
1. Using cascading stylesheets
2. Using a template with placeholders
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It could be useful to have an HTML feature that allows streaming out of order, and the browser would then reorganize the DOM content into the correct order.
But the location-based approach seems promising. I'll try it.
@user22 Oh, you want the browser to fix the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first just to allow the user to see it as soon as possible. It would be great if it could do this without affecting the DOM order, so that the browser can ensure the obtained DOM order matches the visual order.
In other words, stream section 7 first, but make sure the final result (both DOM and visual) is as if all sections had been streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Look at PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
